                    <t:note>
                        
                        <t:ab type="history">The chronicle of King <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS4428Galawdew">Galāwdewos</t:persName> locates ʾAraftā somewhere in <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC6569Tegray">Tǝgrāy</t:placeName>. 
                            According to this chronicle, it was a place where the Christians army became victorious over the Muslims forces with the support of the <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC5111Portug">Portugal</t:placeName>
                            soldiers in<t:date>1542</t:date>. On the other hand, <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS3047Castanho">Miguel de Castanhoso</t:persName>'s account reports the Portuguese army defeated the forces of 
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS1500Ahmad">ʾAḥmad</t:persName> in the same year, as indicated in the chronicle, at a place called <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1400AmbaSa">Amba Śännayti</t:placeName> which is today in the region of 
                            <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1263Adwa">ʿĀdwā</t:placeName>. <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1400AmbaSa">Amba Śännayti</t:placeName> has 70 districts. Therefore, ʾAraftā would probably be a locality in one of the districts of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1400AmbaSa">Amba Śännayti</t:placeName>. </t:ab> 
               
                        
                        
                    </t:note>
                    
